#import "../../common.typ": *

#hl[What is SPI?]

SPI is a *synchronous*, *full-duplex*, *master-slave* serial bus. Unlike UART, a shared *clock line* is provided by the master — no baud rate agreement needed.

#v(0.7em)
#grid(
  columns: (1fr, 1fr, 1fr, 1fr),
  gutter: 0.8em,
  rect(fill: accent.lighten(80%), stroke: accent, radius: 6pt, inset: 11pt)[
    #text(weight: "bold", fill: accent)[Synchronous] \
    #text(size: 14pt)[Clock driven by master. Both sides latch on the same edge.]
  ],
  rect(fill: accent.lighten(80%), stroke: accent, radius: 6pt, inset: 11pt)[
    #text(weight: "bold", fill: accent)[Full-Duplex] \
    #text(size: 14pt)[Data flows in both directions simultaneously on separate wires.]
  ],
  rect(fill: accent.lighten(80%), stroke: accent, radius: 6pt, inset: 11pt)[
    #text(weight: "bold", fill: accent)[Master-Slave] \
    #text(size: 14pt)[Master controls the clock and selects which slave talks.]
  ],
  rect(fill: accent.lighten(80%), stroke: accent, radius: 6pt, inset: 11pt)[
    #text(weight: "bold", fill: accent)[No Addressing] \
    #text(size: 14pt)[Slaves are selected by a dedicated chip select (CS) line.]
  ],
)

#v(0.7em)
Common uses: flash memory, SD cards, ADCs/DACs, displays, sensors.

